# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: artistic-gymnastics-world-championships
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **Antwerp International Gymnastics Tournament** (*Tournois International Gymnastique D'Anvers*), retrospectively regarded as the 1st Artistic Gymnastics World Championships, were held in Antwerp, Belgium, in conjunction with the 27th Belgian Federal Festival, on 14–18 August 1903.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships were purely team events without any individual awards.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual all-round scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual apparatus scores were introduced subsequently.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] As such no actual individual medals were awarded at these games, the below rankings were conferred retrospectively.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1903-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This brief biographical treatment was published at least as far back as 14 January 2017 on the official Facebook website of his alma mater in a photograph album, begun on 29 November 2016, containing other such brief biographical treatments of its notable alumni.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **2nd Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Bordeaux, France, in conjunction with the 31st Federal Festival of France, on April 22–23, 1905.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships consisted at the time only of a team event.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The individual all-round scores were introduced in 1922.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Individual apparatus scores were recognised subsequently retrospectively.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1905-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] An article published in the 10 June 2024 issue of The International Journal of the History of Sport (a peer-reviewed journal) claimed that the BFEG’s (the FIG’s predecessor) archives from before 1950 appear to have been lost.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **3rd Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Prague, Bohemia, in conjunction with the 5th Czech Sokol Slet on 30 June 1907.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] A historic signpost in the sometimes contentious politics of the sport occurred with respect to these championships.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In a 100-year Anniversary Publication of the International Federation of Gymnastics, a past observation of Dr.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Miroslav Klinger, an honorary member of the FIG, was noted with regard to a German magazine article.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In that FIG publication, it is written that an article in a 1907 issue of the German publication Deutsche Turnzeitung "dissuaded the non-slavic nations from participating in the international competition in Prague, by saying the competitors could be threatened by violence.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The goal of the article was to pressure the president of the European Federation into the renunciation of the Prague event.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] †=The website Gymnastics-History.com, in a blog entry about the 1907 World Championships, states that "In 125 Years of the FIG: The Story Goes on, the FIG lists Erben and Charmoille as the high bar champions.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1907-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] In other areas of this competition, also, Vidal was one of the highest scorers.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1909-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **4th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Luxembourg, in conjunction with the 9th Federal Festival of Luxembourg, on August 1, 1909.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1909-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The countries sending teams to the games were France, Bohemia (i.e., the Czechs), Belgium, Carniola (i.e., Slovenia), and Italy.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **Turin International Gymnastics Tournament**, subsequently regarded as the 5th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships, was held in Turin, Italy, in conjunction with the 8th Italian Federal Festival of Gymnastics, on 13 May 1911.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The countries whose teams were officially scored at the tournament were Italy, France, Belgium, Slovenia, Croatia, Luxembourg and Bohemia (i.e., the Czech Sokol team).
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Romania sent a team of gymnasts to the event, but they took part in only some of the exercises, and were not scored for all events.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The championships were purely a team event without any individual awards.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] Similarly, Czechoslovakia did not exist as an independent country at the time, instead Czech competitors competed under the flag of Bohemia.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The team totals were out of a maximum of 1126 points.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The 1 September 1911 issue of the magazine Sokolské besedy reported slightly different team totals for some of these teams, however the ordering was exactly the same.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1911-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This source also reports Erben and Pitl as having placed 11th and 22nd.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1913-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **6th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Paris, France, on the occasion of the 40th anniversary of the "Union des Societes des Gymnastique de France", on November 16, 1913.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1913-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The tournament was held at the Voltaire gymnasium on Rue Japy.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] The **7th Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** were held in Ljubljana, Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes (now Slovenia) on August 11–12, 1922.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] This was the first international tournament arranged under the auspices of FIG at which individual medals for all-round performance were awarded.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/1922-world-artistic-gymnastics-championships] However, the individual medals for apparatus were not awarded at the 1922 tournament, those discussed below were awarded by FIG retrospectively.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The **Artistic Gymnastics World Championships** are the world championships for artistic gymnastics governed by the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG).
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first edition of the championships was held in 1903, exclusively for male gymnasts.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the tenth edition of the tournament, in 1934, women's events are held together with men's events.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The FIG was founded in 1881 and was originally entitled FEG (Fédération Européenne de Gymnastique), but changed its name in 1921, becoming the Fédération Internationale de Gymnastique (FIG); this name change roughly correlates with the actual naming of the World Championships.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Although the first such games were held in 1903, they were not initially entitled the 'World Championships'.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The first competition ever actually referred to as a 'World Championships' at the time was a competition held in 1931 that, while referred to in an official FIG publication as the "First Artistic Men's World Championships", often seems to go ignored by various authorities in the sport.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The championships prior to the 1930s, beginning back in 1903, would eventually be recognized, retroactively, as the World Championships.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Additionally, repeat World All-Around Champion from 1909 and 1913, Marco Torres was also French-Algerian as he was born in Sidi Bel Abbès.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Perhaps the first African delegation was the Egyptian one which offered forth a full male team at the 1950 World Championships in Basel.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the time of these World Championships, a total of 60 male athletes from 6 countries and 53 female athletes from 7 countries comprised the competitive field.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] By the 2013 World Championships, the competition had grown to include 264 men from 71 countries and 134 women from 57 countries.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] As of 2023, over fifty editions of the championships have been staged, and over fifty countries have earned medals in artistic gymnastics events.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The most successful nation, both in gold medal results and total number of medals, is the former Soviet Union (not including medals from its successor states), and China is the second.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The United States is the third most successful country in gold medal results while Japan is the third in total number of medals.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Since the fall of the Iron Curtain, the traditional powerhouses in men's and women's individual still had expressive results: Russia, Belarus, Ukraine, China, United States, Japan, and Romania.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The last two decades were marked by increasing results from two emerging powers: Great Britain and Brazil and at the same period a big decrease in results from Belarus, Romania and Ukraine.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] However, this cycle was broken in 2021, when the COVID-19 pandemic led to the 2020 Summer Olympics to be delayed by one year, the edition scheduled for that year was not cancelled.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] While the Games were held between July and August 2021, the World Championships was allocated to the end of the same year.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] † The FIG (now World Gymnastics) in their 125-year anniversary publication, whereas pre-World War I editions of these championships are concerned, credits the teams and athletes from the Bohemian/Czech lands, then part of Austria-Hungary, as belonging to Czechoslovakia.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] †† There seems to be a history of inconsistency from the FIG's publications regarding whether these 1931 games are considered to be a World Championships.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Last updated after Day 7 of the 2025 World Championships.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Early events such as the 1913 and 1911 championships were purely team events without any individual awards, individual scores were only introduced in 1922, with the first all-round individual men's champion being recognised in that year.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly the first women's championship in 1934 only had medals being awarded to teams, not individuals.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Individual "medals" for these events were therefore only recognised retrospectively and weren't awarded at the time.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Similarly, until 1921 FIG was known as the *European* Gymnastics Federation (*FEG*) and its events were not world championships as such.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Boldface denotes active artistic gymnasts and highest medal count among all artistic gymnasts (including those not included in these tables) per type.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Few non-primary sources state that at the 1938 World Artistic Gymnastics Championships, in Prague, Vlasta Děkanová of Czechoslovakia won 2 or 3 golds on multiple apparatuses.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] The only primary source on the subject, a book officially released by the International Gymnastics Federation containing the results of the World Championships from 1903 to 2005, informs that medals were distributed only in the team all-around event and in the individual all-around event.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Therefore, according to official reports, Děkanová's official number of gold medals is four, two in individual all-round (1934 and 1938) and two in team events (1934 and 1938) - not six or seven.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in five or more events are listed.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below third place are not taken into account.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Results for Germany and West Germany have been combined.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Only nations with medals in three or more events are listed.
[src:artistic-gymnastics-world-championships/artistic-gymnastics-world-championships] Positions below eighth place are not taken into account.
